{"title_page": "1947\u201348 Dumbarton F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n| season             = 1947\u20131948\n| manager            = William Guthrie\n| chairman           = \n| stadium            = Boghead Park, Dumbarton\n| league             = [[1947\u201348 Scottish Football League|Scottish League B Division]]\n| league result      = 11th\n| cup1               = [[1947\u201348 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = Third Round\n| cup2               = [[1947\u201348 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = Prelims\n| cup3               = [[B Division Supplementary Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = Second Round\n| league topscorer   = John Wardlaw (13)\n| season topscorer   = Jackie Cantwell (16)\n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1946\u201347 Dumbarton F.C. season|1946\u201347]]\n| nextseason         = [[1948\u201349 Dumbarton F.C. season|1948\u201349]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1947\u201348''' season was the 64th [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]] season in which [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] competed at national level, entering the [[Scottish Football League]], the [[Scottish Cup]], the [[Scottish League Cup]] and the [[B Division Supplementary Cup|Supplementary Cup]].  In addition Dumbarton competed in the [[Stirlingshire Cup]].\n\n==Scottish Football League==\n{{Main|1947-48 Scottish Football League}}\nA poor start, which saw only one point taken from the first 5 league games, meant that any hopes of challenging for promotion were quickly dashed and eventually Dumbarton finished 11th out of 16 with 25 points - 28 behind champions East Fife.\n\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =13 August 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|team1 =[[Raith Rovers F.C.|R